Coronavirus (COVID-19): stay up to date
Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Chile. The Chilean authorities have introduced measures to limit the spread of the virus. For more information, see the COVID-19 page of this advice. See coronavirus travel advice for guidance on international travel. Sign up for email alerts for Chile travel advice.
Chilean President Sebastian Piñera announced a 90-day ‘National State of Catastrophe’ on Wednesday 18 March 2020. At this time, no tangible measures have been announced – such as restriction of movement - however, we expect such announcements in the coming days at short notice. The Chilean authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus. See COVID-19
The British Embassy Santiago is currently working fully remotely. If you have an urgent consular issues – such as a request for an Emergency Travel Document – you will need to pre-book an appointment online. We are not able to respond to British Nationals who visit the Embassy without a pre-booked appointment.
The Chilean government has announced restrictions on entry at its borders, beginning 18 March 2020. Restriction of entry into Chile will apply to all nationalities, with the exception of Chilean nationals and non-national residents.
The FCO strongly encourage non-resident British nationals in Chile to consider leaving the country, to avoid difficulties while commercial flights remain available.
We are urgently working to get updated information from airlines regarding flights that will be leaving Chile to the UK, which we will be communicating through our online channels: Twitter, Facebook and FCO Travel Advice
Although their switchboards and websites will be very busy we still encourage British nationals to contact their travel agents and airlines to confirm information.
Since 0800 on 15 March, the Chilean authorities have closed all Ports to cruise liners.
The team at the British Embassy in Santiago is in contact with the Chilean Government at a senior level, with local authorities and cruise operators to try to find a resolution to the situation rapidly and provide support to people who need it.
Following civil unrest in October and November 2019 across Chile you may see a police presence in major cities. There is potential for further demonstrations with a risk of violence in Santiago, Valparaiso, Viña del Mar, Antofagasta, Concepcion and other major cities.
In Santiago, protests largely took place in Plaza Baquedano/Plaza Italia and in Las Condes, Providencia and Vitacura districts. In Valparaiso, protests have frequently taken place on a Friday. If protests take place, you should follow the instructions and advice of the local authorities, remain vigilant, monitor local media for updates and avoid protests and demonstrations. Under Chilean law, foreign nationals visiting or living in Chile could be deported for involvement in protests and demonstrations. See Local laws and customs
Public transport is largely running as normal, however, some Santiago Metro stations remain closed. For updated information about public transport, roads and others, you should monitor Chile Reports.
If you plan to travel to Atacama Region (Third Region), be aware that some areas of the region are currently under a ‘state of emergency’ due to floods and landslides. You should check with local authorities before travelling to the region as some roads have been closed.
If you are planning to cross any land border point, you should check with authorities prior to travel.
Around 80,000 British nationals visit Chile each year. Most visits to Chile are trouble-free.
Opportunistic street crime can be a problem in towns and cities, and in areas popular with tourists including airports, bus stations and ports. Take care of your personal belongings at all times and be aware of your surroundings. Carry a photocopy of your passport and keep the original document in a safe place.
There have been incidents involving people being followed from Santiago International Airport to their destinations and then robbed, sometimes at gunpoint. Be aware of your surroundings in and around the airport, when driving away and on arrival at your destination. In case of an incident, do not offer resistance. See Crime
Terrorist attacks in Chile can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
If you need to contact the emergency services, call 131 for an ambulance, 132 for the fire brigade and 133 for police.
The Overseas Business Risk service offers information and advice for British companies operating overseas on how to manage political, economic, and business security-related risks.
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
